const title = 'SQL vs NoSQL: which database, and when (2026)';
const description = 'SQL vs NoSQL in 2026: SQL databases store structured data in related tables with a fixed schema and strong consistency; NoSQL trades some of that for flexible schemas and horizontal scale. The real differences, consistency, scaling, and which to choose.';
const hero = '/img/sql-vs-nosql-2026.jpg';
const faq = [
  { q: 'What is the difference between SQL and NoSQL?', a: 'SQL (relational) databases store data in tables of rows and columns with a fixed, predefined schema, and use SQL to query across related tables - examples are PostgreSQL, MySQL and SQLite. NoSQL is an umbrella term for non-relational stores that use flexible data models (documents, key-value, wide-column, graph) and often relax strict schemas and cross-table joins for flexibility and scale - examples are MongoDB, Redis, Cassandra and DynamoDB. In short: SQL favours structure and consistency; NoSQL favours flexibility and horizontal scale.' },
  { q: 'Is NoSQL faster than SQL?', a: 'Not inherently. NoSQL can be faster for the access patterns it is designed around - simple key lookups, high write throughput, or data that maps cleanly to a single document - and it scales horizontally across many nodes more easily. SQL is often faster and simpler for complex queries that join related data, and modern relational databases are extremely well optimised. Speed depends far more on your data model, indexes and query patterns than on the SQL/NoSQL label.' },
  { q: 'When should I use NoSQL instead of SQL?', a: 'Choose NoSQL when your data is naturally schema-less or rapidly evolving, when you need to scale writes horizontally across many servers, or when your access pattern is mostly simple reads/writes by key (caching, sessions, event logs, large catalogues). Choose SQL when data is highly relational, when you need transactions and strong consistency (payments, inventory, anything where correctness matters), and when you will run varied ad-hoc queries.' },
  { q: 'Can I use both SQL and NoSQL together?', a: 'Yes, and many systems do - it is called polyglot persistence. A common pattern is a relational database as the source of truth for core, consistent data (users, orders) plus a NoSQL store for a specific job: Redis for caching and sessions, a document store for flexible content, or a search engine for full-text. Use each tool where it fits rather than forcing everything into one model.' },
];
